	<h2>Overview</h2>
	<p>
		<em>The Structure of Scientific Revolutions</em> is one of the most influential works in the philosophy 
		of science. Kuhn challenges the traditional view of scientific progress as a linear accumulation of 
		knowledge, instead proposing that science advances through revolutionary paradigm shifts.
	</p>

	<h2>Key Concepts</h2>
	
	<h3>Paradigms</h3>
	<p>
		Kuhn introduces the concept of a "paradigm" as a set of shared assumptions, methods, and standards 
		that define a scientific community. Paradigms provide the framework within which normal science operates.
	</p>

	<h3>Normal Science</h3>
	<p>
		The routine work of scientists operating within an established paradigm, solving puzzles and 
		extending the paradigm's explanatory power. This is the majority of scientific activity.
	</p>

	<h3>Paradigm Shifts</h3>
	<p>
		Revolutionary periods when anomalies accumulate and the existing paradigm becomes inadequate. 
		These shifts are not just theoretical changes but represent fundamental transformations in how 
		scientists view the world.
	</p>

	<h3>Incommensurability</h3>
	<p>
		The idea that competing paradigms may be fundamentally incompatible, making direct comparison 
		difficult. Scientists operating under different paradigms may literally see different things 
		when looking at the same data.
	</p>

	<h2>Why I Want to Read This</h2>
	<p>
		As someone interested in the philosophy of science, epistemology, and how knowledge systems 
		evolve, Kuhn's work seems essential. His ideas about paradigm shifts resonate with how I think 
		about progress in fields like AI and machine learning, where fundamental assumptions are 
		constantly being questioned and revised.
	</p>

